    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The suburb's low stock turnover is one of its defining characteristics. Properties in Fig Tree Pocket are tightly held, and when a home comes to market the buyer pool is smaller than for a mass-market suburb but highly motivated: these are buyers who have been watching the suburb closely, who understand the value of what they are purchasing, and who do not have the option of patient delay when stock is this scarce. Getting the campaign right from the outset is important precisely because the pool of ready buyers in Fig Tree Pocket does not reset quickly if the first approach misses them.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The western corridor around Fig Tree Pocket offers everyday amenity through the Kenmore Village and nearby Indooroopilly Shopping Centre, with the Kenmore SHS catchment serving families in the area. Access to the CBD runs along Moggill Road and through Indooroopilly, and the riverside setting of much of the suburb means that many properties combine a sense of suburban remoteness with a genuinely accessible western Brisbane address. That combination is what the suburb's buyer values, and it is what a campaign needs to communicate with precision.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
